Today, the Parliament of Ukraine in the course of amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code rejected the attempt to repeal the article, according to which the leader of the opposition, Yulia Tymoshenko, was condemned.
The amendment, which would have led to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the bill on mitigation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was deemed unfavorable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider Tymoshenko’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko argues that the verdict is the political site of the regime; in the West, the process has also been suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, according to which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to be ratified.
