Diet of children suffering from obesity: No breakfast and sausage for dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% suffer from obesity.
According to the latest study, children who suffer from obesity usually come from families who lead an unhealthy lifestyle.
We see once again the importance of the environment and patterns of behavior associated with a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage appears on the tables of children suffering from obesity, almost twice as often as in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19% of obese children ate fries for dinner on the eve of a survey related to an educational event called Obesity is no coincidence.
Moreover, the families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports. This, however, concerns most of the families of modern schoolchildren - only 15% of the children said that their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last academic year; it was attended by almost 900 elementary students throughout Bohemia.
The Obesity event was held for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company V<0xC5><0xA1>eobecn<0xC3><0xA1> zvetotn<0xC3><0xAD> poji<0xC5><0xA1>tovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils from 4 to 8 classes have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate athletic load are the main determining factors that cause a rapidly growing number of children who are suffering from either overweight or obese.
“For example, only half of the respondents said that they eat five times a day, on a breakfast-percus-lunch-percus-dinner scheme, which is one of the indispensable conditions for proper nutrition,” said one of the study’s findings.
No lunches and sausages in the evening
Experts warn that even relative details such as the constant time of family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of schoolchildren’s families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone has their own breakfast.
The worst discovery was that in every 10 families, people don’t have breakfast at all.
And yet, breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study found that fried foods are more often used in families with children who are obese.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet refreshments every day (70%).
Although more than 40% of children regularly engage in sports, this figure drops more than twice - to 15% - when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to create their own menu based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
“The food preferences of Czech children aged 12-15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating.”
Their favorite food includes a large number of bitter, meaty and sweet dishes.
“Special anxiety is caused by the great popularity of sweetened soft drinks,” the study concludes.
As the main meal, the pasta defeated the bird with a small excess.
However, the children showed virtually no interest in bean, fish and vegetable dishes.
Aspiration for a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also found that children are willing to change their eating habits, provided they are provided with the appropriate information.
"Many participants in the study's control group demonstrated a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they filled out a questionnaire after the lecture Obesity is not an accident," the project said.
This was especially noticeable, for example, in the case of sweet soft drinks - more children began to prefer them simply water.
In addition, as the main dish, the children more often noted the bird and fish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and baking.
