V Need for Speed: Escape takes place in America.
<0xE2><0x80><0xA2> Review
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and negligent mistakes.
Ambitions have been met to some extent, but that doesn’t matter, as no one clearly wanted to do the extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subheading "Pobeg", there was great hope.
It was expected to shift the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; the demo versions indicated that the game would take a decent place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs away.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, a lot is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the overall impression spoils a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
In fact, this is not a mistake, but an inexplicable deception of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You become part of the story, the main character of which, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by taking part in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your task is to get to New York first.
This idea has a few interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes place along its own route, and individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
It doesn’t feel like the same thing is happening in the game all the time.
Despite the fact that the graphics are on the same level as in the previous parts of the series, it is nice to look at some of the tracks.
However, the game does not cause strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs or high in the snowy mountains is very pleasant.
In addition, the race from time to time revives an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you get into a sandstorm, significantly reducing visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
The individual races are quite well-ordered.
There are only a few varieties, but that’s enough.
For some time you are trying to outrun several opponents (essentially a normal race); then you are trying to improve time (a standard race with a second timer); or you are competing with one opponent.
Among other things, from time to time you run into a police force that makes your task even more complicated.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It’s just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you should help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you would expect (just three to be exact).
In fact, it turns out that it’s good for the game because this property doesn’t get bored; considering all of the above, it’s one of the things that makes the game more enjoyable.
The racing model follows in the footsteps of previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a disadvantage.
If you’re looking for a real-life imitation, you’ll have to look elsewhere.
And yet this driving model is very suitable for dynamic races, although in the market you can find better options.
So far it's very good.
However, after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
From such a game you do not expect complex transformations and collisions, but if you have no idea before the collision with the object, how will your car behave, something is wrong.
Usually, when overtaking or passing the machine in a dense flow, you sometimes slightly touch another machine. And yet sometimes in a virtually similar situation your machine starts to roll madly.
Or it's broken in the air.
It’s not so important thanks to the restart system, but it’s enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are arranged so that if you break or walk away from the track, the game takes you back to the point where it was interrupted.
However, only five reboots are available for each race.
If you use them all, you will have to start the race from the very beginning.
This is useful in case something doesn’t work, but you can’t fully rely on it.
Sometimes reboots are not enough, and you have to learn a separate section of the race.
An important drawback of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to go through in a certain way, otherwise you just won’t sign up.
In other cases, you encounter civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent easily drifting between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you are there, the cars are already positioned in such a way that you need to either circumvent them or slow down the speed.
It doesn’t matter when you’re next to them; everything is arranged so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Rivals also have other advantages.
During the game you discover several places where, regardless of the time, the same opponent beats you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you go in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand in front of you in spite of anything.
The fact is that when it goes in front of you, it worsens your review, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and full of adrenaline, but it is so obvious that it quickly begins to cause irritation.
Too bad, because despite the simple driving model, the game is fun and sometimes so saturated with events that you don’t have time to pay attention to what’s going on around you.
It doesn’t matter what you don’t miss – a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races or something else.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to track the refueling along the way, as it is on them that your car can change, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars – for straight sections of the highway; and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; these are races on individual stages that you will learn during the game.
Here you win for your personal business both medals and points common to the challenges and story modes.
There are many options available to get a higher level of driving: from machines to profile data.
In addition, the profile is associated with the online feature Autolog, which, among other things, compares the results you have achieved with the results of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here’s another drawback that’s hard to understand; it’s an example from the last race in a row.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (let’s assume that’s the case) where you’re racing on the rails in the dark (let’s assume that’s the case).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let’s assume that this is the case) when suddenly a subway train hits you in the back, turning your car into a punched chest.
For a few days, our editorial staff was discussing whether no one really thought for a second at the time of creating the game, or whether its creators really thought we were such fools.
The technical constituent of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from a videographer is mostly pleasant, sometimes even stunning.
Although it is unfortunate that at some critical moments, the quality of the recording, sometimes quite significantly, decreases.
This is especially true of events with a large number of participants, where a good record wouldn’t help you much either.
Sound is fine; the soundtrack is for the amateur.
In order to please as wide a youth audience as possible, the soundtrack has ‘compositions from different styles’; but it’s unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: Escape is rather messy.
If the game had avoided clearly unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS over the past few years.
Either way, the game leaves a sense of incompleteness.
Of course, it’s good fun, but be prepared for the fact that the shortcomings will blind you like the headlights of the airport.
