History of the brand:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find a word that best expresses IMB’s strategy, the closest one is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered to be very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company’s longevity was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson the Elder.
He believed in his motto that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
What’s more, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant movement towards the future.
