IBM's History: From Cheese Knife to Space Flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Computing, Tabulation, Recording Corporation" was quite complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924. Originally it was called the brand used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history begins in the 1880s.
They owned technologies such as the legendary "table clock", i.e. clocks that record the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the board of trustees of the company.
Flint hired a rival company director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The CEO then put the founder of IBM in the shadows – Watson’s ideas remain the foundation of an inviolable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, started producing and selling various business equipment – from cheese knives and butchers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and a large-scale expansion of the company to all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his place in the chair of the director was taken by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control space flights — to Mercury, Saturn, and 1969 — human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers – the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined the computer standards of the time, called the IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, at the same time buying the consulting division of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and services with high value added.
In the last three years, IBM has achieved great success with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make reasonable use of technology in areas where it has not yet been planned, and to improve the road situation and urban management.
In the field of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM’s traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also manages a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Headquarters in Central and Eastern Europe are located in Prague, where a world-class research group on speech recognition is also working.
