The dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourism agencies were able to operate in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies at the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists went on holiday to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter was required from that country; otherwise individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
A currency permit was required for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain cash (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit remains to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus undergone a real revolution.
While until 1989 vacation in the DDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we are no longer aware of, is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia at the moment, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This led to a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not be satisfied with the trips to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring your own food (canned food, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krona. After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines. Compared to the past, airfares have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world, except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. High demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been taking Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter, flights from the Czech Republic will go to twelve exotic destinations.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, which symbolizes our post-revolution development, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the requirement to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Our country has thus forever joined the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than CZK 15,000 per person during their vacation abroad, including their destination expenses.
