There are so many.
Among the first to come to mind are Gizer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukovsky...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in maintaining the relevance of the granite, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a bit of a break from the word grunge.
When I think about him, he reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all of those that came along at the same time, and if it matters now, I think it's great because it's kind of cool when I'm making music.
At first your music was darker, and now it has become more positive.
How do you explain this change?
