Fuhimori was hospitalized again for medical examination.
Former President Alberto Fuhimori was hospitalized in a state hospital on Tuesday for an examination of the loss of muscle strength seen in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fuhimori, 72, who has been sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his tenure (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone surgery four times and is under observation.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his personal doctor, told television channel N that Fuhimori will be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aginaga said that, in his opinion, Fuhimori should be a candidate for a pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he did not want this because he knew he was innocent.
He underwent four operations for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms in weight, to which were added other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure and problems with blood circulation in the legs, the doctor said.
Fuhimori has been in prison since September 2007, in the National Police Department of Special Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people by the forces of the army's destruction squad, which acted in secret during the first years of his rule.
Muhika is going to Mexico to strengthen political ties.
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Muhikoi and consisting of several ministers and businessmen will arrive on Tuesday with a visit to Mexico to expand trade between the two countries and to start negotiations on the region’s political problems.
Muhika will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderon, the most important point of the comprehensive plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and meetings with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the schedule.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be “convenient for the exchange of information on the issue of political relations between the two nations,” the South American leadership said on its website.
According to local media, Muhika is seeking Calderon’s support for Uruguay in an incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the tax havens list at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that sparked Uruguay’s protest and a recall for his ambassador’s consultations in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group created from the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, in essence, an agreement with the South American country since January this year on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Government of Uruguay has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements in order to leave this “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development, composed of countries that do not enjoy international standards of tax co-operation.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
