Colom guarantees Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Alvaro Colom said on Tuesday that Alfonso Portillo's extradition process had begun, so that he could answer in the United States for a conspiracy to launder $70 million.
That concludes the process by which Guatemala responded to the request of the northern country, which demanded the extradition of Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colum said his decision was related to the independence of the judicial and executive authorities, taking into account that the court of first instance had already signed the extradition.
He claimed that during his term of office he had not "handed over" legal decisions and had taken all extradition procedures he had ever known about.
Along with Portillo Sergio Ruano Marroquin will be extradited for murder and serious bodily harm, as well as Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Kolom has done shows the executive process after all the legal and constitutional courts were exhausted in order to prosecute the former Head of State from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court, Portillo will be extradited once with a decision on his legal status in Guatemala and a guarantee of his human rights.
Portillo was found not guilty of wasting Q120 million in the Department of Defense during the presidential term, which was a process prior to extradition, but the Department of Public Relations filed an appeal and reopened the case.
