MSS Announces Search Program for the Obesity Gene
Social Protection Leads Study to Find the Gene of Obesity in Children and Young People; Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which has been dubbed the “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescenthood” protocol, which will give a count of signs associated with obesity.
In his statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in the field of Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center Miguel Cruz Lopez explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers was assembled.
The team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday from 8:00 a.m. children will be tested.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Quautemoca (west Mexico), and since October 8, the events are held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyote (east Mexico).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North Mexico).
He explained that the aim of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, and the main goal is to bring together 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with parental permission and under their supervision to fill out individual dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), measurement of blood pressure and levels of glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are related to childhood) will be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health care professionals’ concerns about an alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there was growth in just 6 years: in boys, 77 percent were obese, in girls, 47 percent were overweight, and in the case of overweight, there was also significant growth,” MSSI said.
He said that the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that on average Mexicans are 65 percent descendants of American Indians, 30 percent descendants of Europeans, and five percent descendants of Africans, and this condition affected genes that are linked to diabetes and obesity.
He explained that basically, the consequence of obesity genetics is the inability of the body to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that a direct benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children that can identify if they have any degree of excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with complete confidentiality, the doctors pass it on in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that need to be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main reasons that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, having the most of the day at home in front of the TV, and the use of transportation in small groups.
