He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular masses called asphalts, and others of which are low molecular masses called maltenes, which together give the road covering its characteristic.
The viscous behavior of a bitumen is that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains its almost solid state, while at very low temperatures it retains its solid state.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineering expert.
The chimfac scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the topmost layers is bitumen, composed of small stones dropped into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting efforts, it helps the forces to distribute very well on the road cover.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt coating, he added, the last layer is placed, which is called the wear layer, which is made of a small stone, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the transport wheels, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
