The North Stream, a new gateway to the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is expected to supply the equivalent of gas to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between an orchestral performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the North Stream, a new pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte have together turned a symbolic valve controlling the influx of Russian gas into Western Europe.
Under the new gas pipeline, an additional 27,500 million cubic meters of gas will enter Western Europe each year via the first 1,224 km long pipeline that connects the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55 thousand million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding the passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will be more difficult to influence Russia, threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is striving for greater security of its supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of a direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already on the way.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” Fion said, opening the pipeline, demonstrating how important large gas contracts are both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom’s leaders, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields that remained since World War II.
“One hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesperson for North Stream.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing equal to the weight of 242 Eiffel towers, without cracks along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers gave up on it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state company would settle on its shores forever.
“In the event of an accident, we will shut down the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
So, in the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers who designed seams designed to run only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the condition of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot, which pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by the flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of the gas is carried out only by its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement the project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The others are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture, called the North Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are located in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gasprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually being transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be around 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay for their expenses, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The pipeline runs from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to the sandy coast, planted by coniferous trees.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the output terminal of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
