About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week of employment of disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charities policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is still twice as high as the average, 19% versus 9% for the general population.
Disheartening?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
“In 15 years, we will make significant progress.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not 2, but 3 times higher.”
“But there is still a lot of work ahead.”
It must be said that there is still a lot to be done about disability barriers in employment.
Among them, 37% are older than 50 years old (17% on average).
They are more likely to have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and that are the essence of the problem,” says Christian Grapene, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association on behalf of Cité showed that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “presented themselves consistent people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally impaired.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of disabled workers, set out in the law adopted in 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 represent 2.6 per cent.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blan, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxable" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>606 to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>480 million).
“The 2005 law, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on the company,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects the increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers versus 82 per cent of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
